 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uhummerlein.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hummerlein</A> at: 3/24/02 11:41:45 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ufricka.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fricka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/24/02 7:12:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseoutsidenorrath.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6848.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: If you could go anywhere in the world, where would you g</span><hr size=1> Hmm ye've got a week and have to stay in the same hotel?<br>
<br>
I enjoyed my stay in England so I say go to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> London</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, lots of spots are day trips away from it and you can see castles there. Transportation wise, the Underground is easy to use and goes to a bunch of places and the train system is fair as well.<br>
<br>
In London itself, be sure to visit the toy floor in Harrods and catch some plays. There's a very puny one that's been running forever, email me if you want the name and I'll dig it up. The Tower of London's got a nice collection of shiny things... but try very hard not to steal them <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Speaking of thieves and getting caught, while in London, I took a visit to Baker street... no 221B though, hehe (be sure to tell your dad that btw).<br>
<br>
My second recommendation based on your requirements is to go to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Rome</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. While it was initially such a disappointment to me due to the jarring juxtapostion with what I had in my head of &quot;ancient Rome&quot;, I ended up enjoying it quite a bit. Language is not much of a barrier and you will definitely feel more &quot;away from home&quot; than if you were to go to England.<br>
<br>
Other than those two, I think you'll have fun where ever you decide to go. Travel is always an adventure.<br>
